    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT374-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">aṟattoṭu niṉṟamai tōḻi kiḻattikku uraittatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told to HER by the confidante as a [way of]
                    standing firm in duty. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT374">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> entaiyum yāyu muṇarak kāṭṭi</l>
                    <l> yoḷitta ceyti veḷippaṭak kiḷantapiṉ</l>
                    <l> malaikeḻu veṟpaṉ ṟalaivan tirappa</l>
                    <l> naṉṟupuri koḷkaiyi ṉoṉṟā yiṉṟē</l>
                    <l> muṭaṅka liṟaiya tūṅkaṇaṅ kurīi</l>
                    <l> nīṭirum peṇṇait toṭutta</l>
                    <l> kūṭiṉu mayaṅkiya maiya lūrē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l> As my father and mother,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> after having shown that they had come to know,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> [and] after it was expressed clearly, that [my] secret action</l>
                    <l rend="indent9"> had become public,</l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> [and] since [the thing] with the man from the mountains</l>
                    <l rend="indent6"> had come to pass [anyhow] <note place="foot">Difficult: <term xml:lang="ta"> veṟpaṉ talai vantu </term>. Another possibility is: "after they (the parents) had come to the place of the man from the mountains". (See Wilden 1999: 233f. + n. 31). </note>      ,
                </l>
                <l rend="indent6"> begged [him to marry me], <note place="foot">For the lines 1-3 there are several alternatives. For an extensive discussion see Wilden 1999: 219, 232f. (versus Tieken 1997: 295f.). Here just the different possible renderings are listed. </note>
                </l>
                <l> [the village] became one in the maxim of desiring [to do] good,</l>
                <l rend="indent6"> more so than the nest</l>
                <l rend="indent"> of the Tūṅkanam bird with bent wings, <note place="foot"> For a discussion about the identity of the bird see Tieken 1997: 297f., contra Wilden 1999: 234, n. 32. </note>
                </l>
                <l rend="indent2"> linked with the long, dark Palmyra tree,</l>
                <l> – the village in confused pride.</l>

                <lg type="alternate" sameAs="1-3b" resp="#Cam">
                    <l rend="indent"> After I (the confidante) had expressed clearly, so that it
                            comes out,</l>
                    <l rend="indent8"> [our] secret action,</l>
                    <l> showing [it], so that they realised, to my father and mother,</l>
                    <l> [and] when the man from the mountains came to beg [for her hand], ...</l>

                    <lg type="alternate" sameAs="1-3c">
                        <l rend="indent"> When the man from the mountains,</l>
                        <l> after he had shown, so that my father and mother realise,</l>
                        <l> [and] expressed clearly, so that [it] comes out, [our] secret
                                action,</l>
                        <l rend="indent9"> came to beg, ... <note place="foot"> The third possibility is to take <term xml:lang="ta"> veṟpaṉ </term> as the subject of the first three lines. The advantage would be that the subject would actually be there and would not have to be taken as implied. But from the point of view of contents this seems less probable and in any case it has no explicit parallels elsewhere. Further disadvantages would be the redundancy of the statements in lines 1+2, and the missing representation of  <term xml:lang="ta"> talai </term> in line 3.   </note>
                        </l>

                    </lg>

                </lg>
            </lg>
        </div>
